Jude 03 Oct 2013, 08:02

Thank you Eyestein, you've reinforced my point and its nice to hear from someone who understands how myopia works. I've read a lot of posts on here and I get frustrated by the excitement a -20 prescription creates with the attendant "I bet she's blind without them comments". Well yes she would certainly be visually impaired with an rx like that but in real terms no more so than someone with a -10 rx. A person with a -5 rx would see worse in poor light than someone with -20 in bright sunlight too so what I was trying to say was that numbers aren't the whole story. My right eye is now over -14 (my left is all but blind) and there is absolutely no difference in terms of what I can do without correction than there was 20 years ago.

Eyestein 03 Oct 2013, 07:40

Thanks Jude

At least now we know where you're coming from.

Numbers like -3, -6, and -9 are significant enough in that they mark the commonly accepted boundaries between mild myopia, moderate myopia, severe myopia, and extreme myopia. In terms of useful or functional vision 9 and 15 dioptres of myopia is little different but there is certainly a large difference in poorness of vision between 3 and 6 dioptres of myopia.

Jude 02 Oct 2013, 08:47

Well if it means that much to people on here I think I would have been about -9 or -10 in both eyes back then. My point was that if I'd said I was -5 or -20 what difference would it make? There are numerous factors involved in whether one can distinguish a pair of glasses on the floor, including the colour of the frames, style of frame, colour of the floor, lighting conditions. I think people on here place undue importance on rx numbers. The fact was that my vision was sufficiently impaired to prevent me immediately spotting my glasses on the floor from a standing position (particularly with tears in my eyes).

Yes, her vision is possibly very poor even with her glasses. Most people with nystagmus (eye twitching) have mild to severe vision impairment because of it. The condition can affect depth perception and even balance. It is rare for a person with nystagmus to be legally able to drive a car.

In every scene in whch she is moving around somone appears to holding onto her or guiding her. In one outdoor scene in MovieRoom she descends a set of stairs rather cautiously while holding onto someone (and while wearing her glasses). It looks like it's more than just affection.

myofan 15 Aug 2009, 16:06

R Ed,

With a Windows XP computer, if you've installed 7-zip, the best technique is this:

1. Place the .001 and .002 files into the same directory.

2. Select and right-click the .001 file. Choose '7-zip\Open archive'. The 7-zip dialog should appear and the file "juicykali_glasses_fun.flv" should be visible.

3. Select the FLV file and choose "Extract". A dialog called "Copy" should appear. The directory where the .001 and .002 files are located sgould be visible in the dialog's "Copy to" box.

4. Click "OK" to extract the FLV file.

There are probably other ways to accomplish the above, but this is probably the simplest. If you have a Mac, I don't know how to help you other than to suggest that you start 7-zip, select the .001 file and click "Extract".
